How can I determine the significance of overlaps?

When genetics datasets are integrated with proteomics data, the overlaps are statistically tested and the results are made available to users. The statistical significance can help to determine, for example, the overlap of interactors and genes genetically linked to a particular disease.

The input file formats used in the “Integrated Plots”" for SNPs, genes of interest, and InWeb input are identical to those used for Venn diagrams.



Hypergeometric distribution is used to perform gene list enrichment analysis between experimental proteomics data and 1) user’s uploaded gene list(s) and/or 2) known protein-protein interactions from InWeb.

Using the InWeb interactors as an example, first, the overlap between experimental data and InWeb_IM database is found (population) followed by identification of its subset that passed user defined significance threshold (success in population). Second, for the chosen bait, list of literature known interacting proteins from the InWeb_IM database is identified and overlapped the pull down data (sample). Proteins that passed the user-defined significance threshold and found in InWeb_IM are then identified (success in sample). Hypergeometric test is run to calculate statistical significance of having given amount of successes in population, and the Venn diagram is generated to visualize the overlap of population and sample.

When determining the significnace of overlaps for user uploaded gene lists, the population is identified as the overlap between experimental data and HGNC database. Genoppi hosts data with HGNC unified nomenclature system and the population is limited to the gene universe with gene nomenclatures using HGNC symbols.

User can adjust the analysis thresholds during the analyses and have the changes (hypergeometric p value and counts) reflected immediately in the Venn diagrams.


Different categories of Venn diagam output


The counts in each field are based on unique gene names.

1. p value: hypergeometric p-value

2. population (N): subset of gene nomenclatures from proteomics data found in HUGO Gene Nomenclature Committee (guidelines for Human Gene Nomenclature) (total number of genes)

3. number of success in population (n): category A represents proteomics data present in HGNC database that passes the user defined significance threshold (all significant bait interactors)

4. sample (S): user uploaded genes found in HGNC database OR InWeb interactors found in proteomics data


Multiple lists of genes of interest

If multiple gene lists are uploaded, denoted by different columns in one text file, Venn diagram representation and hypergeometric p-value for each list will be generated and calculated. User is able to cycle through different gene lists by clicking on the “down” arrow.
